  <hr color="#800080"/>
  <p style="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0">
  </p>
  <p style="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0">
   The sign "THIS" can be used to mean 
	"here" as in "this place."
  </p>
  <p style="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0">
   <br/>
   THIS / here:
   <br/>
   <img border="0" height="224" src="/images/here-e1.jpg" width="213"/>
   <img border="0" height="224" src="/images/here-e2.jpg" width="213"/>
   <br/>
  </p>
  <font face="Arial">
   <hr color="#800080"/>
  </font>
  <p style="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0">
   <br/>
   <font face="Arial">
    You can also indicate "here" as in the "immediate vicinity" by pointing at the floor, raising your hands an
  inch then lowering them an inch.
    <br/>
    <br/>
    "Right here in this very place."
    <br/>
    <iframe allow="autoplay; encrypted-media" allowfullscreen="" frameborder="0" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/-LllUQJj1aM?rel=0" width="560">
    </iframe>
   </font>
  </p>
  <p style="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0">
   <font face="Arial">
    <img border="0" height="226" src="/images/hereb1.jpg" width="269"/>
    <img border="0" height="226" src="/images/hereb4.jpg" width="269"/>
    <br/>
   </font>
  </p>
  <p style="margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0">
   Notes:
   <br/>
   The pointing version of HERE is more of a "right here" or "this very place."  
	The pointing version can be used at the end of the sign "come" to mean "come
   <em>
    here
   </em>
   ." 
	The point at the floor version is also used as a common single-sign response 
	to "where" questions:  "Where's the party?" 
	"Here."
   <br/>
   The flat hand version is the general sign for HERE and means "this location" in general.
  </p>
